<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-063-346 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 211 369</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Sept 8 1991 v140 pF9(N) pF9(L) 32 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A pen mightier than a password: computers that can recognize asignature are coming to market. (signature verification software)(Technology) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazigi, Monique P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Signature verification software, which has been under developmentfor many years, will be offered as an option with the NCR 3125Notepad hand-held computer in Oct 1991.andP;  The software, which willallow a user to sign in instead of entering a password, is fromConfirma Technology Corp. According to Richard A. Marciano,chairman at Confirma, there are many possible uses for signatureverification.andP;  The technology could even make bank checksobsolete.andP;  Signature verification is said to be dependable:signatures that seem alike to average persons can be revealed asforgeries.andP;  Confirma's program uses the way a person appliespressure in signing a name, but other technologies workdifferently.andP;  Communication Intelligence Corp (CIC), RedwoodShores, CA, is said to be working on a technology that does notuse pressure points because a pressure-point system depends toomuch on the special pen that must be used.andP;  The CIC technologyuses several signatures to establish a range of signaturepatterns.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Confirma Technology Corp. (Product development)Communication Intelligence Corp. (Product development).andO;Product:   NCR 3125 (Portable computer) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Signature verificationAccess RightsSecurityID EquipmentProduct DevelopmentNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Computer analysis of signature. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>